    it no longer points into valid live storage.                                
                                                                                
    Program state walkthrough:                                                  
                                                                                
                                                                                
     std::vector<int> v = {1, 2, 3, 4};                                         
                                                                                
                                                                                
    v initially contains:                                                       
                                                                                
                                                                                
     {1, 2, 3, 4}                                                               
                                                                                
                                                                                
    Its size is 4. Its capacity is at least 4, and in a typical implementation  
    here it is likely exactly 4.                                                
                                                                                
    Then:                                                                       
                                                                                
                                                                                
     auto it = v.begin() + 2;                                                   
                                                                                
                                                                                
    it points to the third element of the original vector storage:              
                                                                                
                                                                                
     *it == 3                                                                   
                                                                                
                                                                                
    Conceptually:                                                               
                                                                                
                                                                                
     v:  [1, 2, 3, 4]                                                           
               ^                                                                
               it                                                               
                                                                                
                                                                                
    Then the code appends 1000 more elements:                                   
                                                                                
                                                                                
     for (int i = 0; i < 1000; ++i) {                                           
         v.push_back(i);                                                        
     }                                                                          
                                                                                
                                                                                
    std::vector stores its elements in a contiguous dynamically allocated       
    buffer. When push_back grows the vector beyond its current capacity, the    
    vector allocates a new, larger buffer, moves/copies the old elements into   
    it, and frees the old buffer.                                               
                                                                                
    When that happens, all existing iterators, pointers, and references into    
    the old vector storage are invalidated.                                     
                                                                                
    So after one of the push_back calls reallocates v, this iterator:           
                                                                                
                                                                                
     it                                                                         
                                                                                
                                                                                
    still contains an address pointing into the old buffer, but that old        
    buffer has been deallocated.                                                
                                                                                
    At the end of the loop, v contains 1004 elements:                           
                                                                                
                                                                                
     {1, 2, 3, 4, 0, 1, 2, ..., 999}                                            
                                                                                
                                                                                
    But it still points to the old freed allocation. Therefore this line:       
                                                                                
                                                                                
     *it                                                                        
                                                                                
                                                                                
    attempts to read an int from deallocated memory. AddressSanitizer reports   
    that as:                                                                    
                                                                                
                                                                                
     Use of deallocated memory                                                  
                                                                                
                                                                                
    The root defect is retaining a std::vector iterator across operations that  
    may reallocate the vector, then dereferencing that stale iterator.          
                                                                                
    A minimal local fix is to store an index instead of an iterator and look    
    the element up after the push_back operations:                              
                                                                                
                                                                                
     #include <cstdio>                                                          
     #include <vector>                                                          
                                                                                
     int main()                                                                 
     {                                                                          
         std::vector<int> v = {1, 2, 3, 4};                                     
                                                                                
         std::size_t index = 2;                                                 
                                                                                
         for (int i = 0; i < 1000; ++i) {                                       
             v.push_back(i);                                                    
         }                                                                      
                                                                                
         std::printf("element via index: %d\n", v[index]);                      
         return 0;                                                              
     }                                                                          
                                                                                
                                                                                
    Because appending to a vector does not change the logical index of          
    existing elements, v[2] is still the element originally pointed to by it.   
                                                                                
    If the intent was specifically to preserve the original value, not the      
    position, then store the value before mutating the vector:                  
                                                                                
                                                                                
     #include <cstdio>                                                          
     #include <vector>                                                          
                                                                                
     int main()                                                                 
     {                                                                          
         std::vector<int> v = {1, 2, 3, 4};                                     
                                                                                
         int element = v[2];                                                    
                                                                                
         for (int i = 0; i < 1000; ++i) {                                       
             v.push_back(i);                                                    
         }                                                                      
                                                                                
         std::printf("element value: %d\n", element);                           
         return 0;                                                              
     }                                                                          
                                                                                
                                                                                
    Another possible local fix is to reserve enough capacity before taking the  
    iterator:                                                                   
                                                                                
                                                                                
     #include <cstdio>                                                          
     #include <vector>                                                          
                                                                                
     int main()                                                                 
     {                                                                          
         std::vector<int> v = {1, 2, 3, 4};                                     
                                                                                
         v.reserve(v.size() + 1000);                                            
                                                                                
         auto it = v.begin() + 2;                                               
                                                                                
         for (int i = 0; i < 1000; ++i) {                                       
             v.push_back(i);                                                    
         }                                                                      
                                                                                
         std::printf("element via iter: %d\n", *it);                            
         return 0;                                                              
     }                                                                          
                                                                                
                                                                                
    This works because if reserve successfully allocates enough capacity ahead  
    of time, the following push_back calls will not reallocate, so it remains   
    valid. However, this is more fragile because it depends on accurately       
    reserving enough capacity before all future insertions.                     
                                                                                
    The more thorough root-cause fix is to avoid designs that keep std::vector  
    iterators, references, or raw pointers alive across vector-mutating         
    operations that may change capacity. Prefer one of these patterns:          
                                                                                
                                                                                
     // Store an index.                                                         
     std::size_t index = 2;                                                     
     // mutate vector                                                           
     use(v[index]);                                                             
                                                                                
                                                                                
    or:                                                                         
                                                                                
                                                                                
     // Store the value if you need the old value.                              
     int saved = v[2];                                                          
     // mutate vector                                                           
     use(saved);                                                                
                                                                                
                                                                                
    or recompute the iterator after mutation:                                   
                                                                                
                                                                                
     std::size_t index = 2;                                                     
                                                                                
     for (int i = 0; i < 1000; ++i) {                                           
         v.push_back(i);                                                        
     }                                                                          
                                                                                
     auto it = v.begin() + index;                                               
     std::printf("element via fresh iter: %d\n", *it);                          
                                                                                
                                                                                
    Recommendation                                                              
                                                                                
    Fix the code by not dereferencing an iterator that was saved before         
    push_back calls. The safest minimal fix is to store the index and           
    reacquire the element after the vector mutations:                           
                                                                                
                                                                                
     #include <cstdio>                                                          
     #include <vector>                                                          
                                                                                
     int main()                                                                 
     {                                                                          
         std::vector<int> v = {1, 2, 3, 4};                                     
                                                                                
         std::size_t index = 2;                                                 
                                                                                
         for (int i = 0; i < 1000; ++i) {                                       
             v.push_back(i);                                                    
         }                                                                      
                                                                                
         std::printf("element via index: %d\n", v[index]);                      
         return 0;                                                              
     }                                                                          
                                                                                
                                                                                
    If you truly need to use an iterator, recompute it after the push_back      
    loop, or call reserve before taking the iterator and ensure no later        
    operation exceeds the reserved capacity.                                    
                                                                                
